deck_excerpt: A budget Yu-Gi-Oh! deck capable of playing the metagame!
deck_description:
I feel as though the Materiactor engine has been completely overlooked. I, myself, was caught up in finding a deck that wants level 3 normal monsters as part of its engine, but Prima Materiactor changes all of that. Instead, you're left with a tight engine that stacks and adds whatever piece you need to keep your deck moving. 

In virtual world, the level 3 access keeps you in line with the deck's core game-plan while adding a very recursive draw engine with Exgard adding whatever pieces you need back to the hand. Small world is a must have in the deck as any card in the deck is a bridge to any other card in the deck.

deck_name: the true cancer of all worlds
deck_description: cancer

This deck basically focuses on summoning Crooked Cook and winning under Exodia The Forbidden One's effect.

 

If your opponent doesn't have anything that can get rid of Crooked Cook like tribute summoning under the effect of Kaiju or inflicting to your life points under the effect of cards that can do piercing damage or direct attack like Toon Monsters for example, then it's most likely you're going to win by either make them wait longer until you get all parts of Exodia in your hands or they basically just go surrender.

 

So basically you need to summon Crooked Cook using the Right-Hand Shark as an XYZ material and it's required because the effect this monster is if it's used as an XYZ material, the XYZ monster will automatically gain that can't be destroyed by battle and by the passive effect of Crooked Cook it will be indestructible unless your opponent uses it as a material for a tribute summon.

 

This is just a troll deck and just an experiment but for some reason it still kinda works.

deck_excerpt: Final Countdown Win ft. World + Chaos Beast + Carbon
deck_description:
Greetings! Once upon a time, I made this deck thanks to Princess and win with Final Countdown. Now, I did it with Chaos Beast instead because what if Princess is banned? Let's find out.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Bring forth Tethys by replacing Capricious/Aces/Corobane and draw your whole deck...

  • Whenever you draw a Fairy, reveal it to draw another card with Tethys. You can keep it going until you can't draw anymore.
  • If you hit non-Fairy, you stop movement. So, continue with Ixchel and alike to trigger Tethys again.
  • Always use "Arcana Force XV" in-hand to fetch what would be otherwise brick by Tethys, which is "Light Barrier".
  • Know that card draw has to be caused by an effect, not as cost, in order to draw a card with Tethys. For example, using "Upstart Goblin", seen in Side Deck, won't do any help for Tethys but "Into the Void" will. Remember this rule well.

2) If Tethys + Aces are together, Link Summon Insulator with them. Otherwise, place Rain and Lebellman onto Pendulum Zones to Pendulum Summon 2 x Carbon + Capricious + Orange. Also, activate "Final Countdown" and "Light Barrier".

3) XYZ Summon Starring Knight with 2 x Carbon as materials. Then, use Knight to Special Summon The World and pick the outcome as heads thanks to "Light Barrier" to be able to skip your opponent's turn by sending two monsters you control to GY.

4) Synchro Summon Chaos Beast with Capricious + Orange. At that moment, Carbon asks you to shuffle itself on top of your Main Deck, which is essential to not deck-out for 20 turns forward.

5) End your turn and use The World to send Beast + Knight to GY, in order to be able to do what was explained in #3. When it's your move, bring forth Carbon + Beast for The World and repeat until you win with Final Countdown...

  • With many LIGHT and DARK monsters available at your arsenal, reviving Beast won't be an issue, provided that you use Beast to retrieve banished monsters into your hand. Afterwards, Pendulum Summon them and use these as resources for The World.
  • No matter what you do, don't forget to send Carbon to GY for The World at all costs to not deck-out by accident.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Into The Void" can be found either within "The Infinite Void" or "Life Force Control System" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Darklord Ixchel" can be found either within "The Opening Act of an Apocalypse" or "Deceitful Wings of Darkness" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Trickstar Corobane" can be found within "Essence of Flora and Ocean" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Tokusano Shinkyojin" can be found within "Crystal Realm Defier" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Chicken Game" can be found within "The Most Dangerous Race of the Cosmos!" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Final Countdown" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 UR!

- "World Soul - Carbon" can be found either within "Hope Sprouting in the Spring Breeze" or "The Ones Who Serve Ra" Secret Packs to save 60 SR!

- "Arcana Force XXI - The World" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 360 SR and 240 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Finalized deck list after much testing
deck_description:
My last deck list for Live☆Twin Fiendsmith Unchained kinda popped off even though it was just a rough draft, and I have spent all week testing this deck to find what new innovations i could bring to the list, so I just wanted to share this list and my thoughts about the deck.

First major change I made was removing an engraver and a tract. This was simply too much for the main deck fiendsmith cards. Being able to turn the Ki-sikil link monsters makes the extra fiendsmith cards not as neccesary because of how easy it is to make requiem in hands that dont have any fiendsmith cards in them.

Next change i made was removing the Abominable Unchained Soul. there really wasnt a reason to include it in the deck, it almost never came up and there are better cards to search with Yama or the unchained spell, it also doesnt have the ability to make Caesar unlike the other good unchained cards.

With this newfound space in the deck I was able to slot in 3 imperms. Having ash blossom as the only handtrap was a major throw. The deck is able to play through interuption pretty well, but it definetly struggles against a fully formed end board that i wasnt able to stop because i didnt draw a handtrap.

A minor change I made was removing 1 Lil-la from the main deck for a Ki-sikil Frost. Normaling Frost can also act as a starter just like normal Ki-sikil (albeit a weaker one.) Also, having Frost in your hand when your normal summon Lil-la gets interrupted, or searching it with sunny snitch when you already opened a Live☆Twin. The utility of this card is definetly something i looked over when I was building the original deck.

The final change I made was taking a solemn out of the side deck for a copy of the big Evil★Twin main deck monster. At one point during testing I was struggling to find a way the deck could get over larger monsters. Something that worried me was my opponent making a giant unaffected tower that i had no out for. This was my best solution for that. I think that 4400ATK was plenty and you only need one copy of it because Trouble Sunny gives quick access to it paired with non-destroying non-targeting removal.

If I you have any questions, please feel free to ask in the comments. I check my decks often, so I will most likely respond.

A new semi-splashable Yugioh engine has hit the block, and its themes of Biblical creation and angelic imagery one of the best designs I've seen in this game to date! YCS Providence was this strategy's first major event to perform on the big stage, and it actually reached top 32! Inspired by Steven Wind's top 32 YCS Providence list, this Regenesis deck uses Kashtira and Fiendsmith cards to enable it to outresource opponents in simplified gamestates (all too common nowadays with everydeck sporting 15+ handtraps)!
 
The deck is very simple to play, so I'm not making a detailed strategy guide on it. Basically, you bait interruption with your Kashtira/Fiendsmith cards, then you set-up with your Regenesis monsters! If you end up getting negated a lot, remember that any 2 monsters is full Fiendsmith combo thanks to Moon of the Closed Heaven.
 
Regenesis basically ends at minimum with a "book of the moon" flip face down effect with Regenesis Birth - or if your graveyard/banished has a lot of Regenesis in it, you can summon them en-masse. The basic combo is Regenesis Archfiend -> Regenesis -> Regenesis Lord -> Summons itself banishing Archfiend then sets Birth from deck. This interruption seems relatively little, but augmented by Fiendsmith, Kashtira and handtraps, it can be difficult for your opponent to face, especially since all three engines recur everyturn. This deck also has 12 handtraps/staple slots, making it easier to play 1st and second. You can also beat over monsters relatively easily, since most monsters in this deck are freely summoned and have 2000+ ATK.

The Extra Deck are mostly cards for the Fiendsmith deck, and can be changed anytime to suit your playstyle. Honestly, this deck can do without the entire Fiendsmith package and can be played purely with Kashtira! The Extra Deck can be used as fodder for Pot of Extravagance or Super Polymerization in that deckbuild.

Kashtira and Regenesis also has the funny distinction of having their ace cards named "Birth" so you can call this deck "double birth control!" Thought that was pretty funny. xD

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Use the radioactive power of the Materiactor cards to turbo rank 3s and search for hand traps from the deck!
deck_description: Couple different engines - Materiactor of course but also some goblin biker for added consistency/disruption with gabonga, and psychic level 3s to extend and play through hand traps

The hand is mightier than the field.
In Domain Format, it's commonly believed that handtraps are rare due to the 60-card deckbuilding requirement. Today, we’re turning that idea on its head—with a deck where two-thirds of the cards are handtraps.

Deckmaster: Wish Dragon 
Domain Restriction: LIGHT // EARTH // DRAGON 
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into 2 broad categories:

  • Handtrap Negates
  • Hooligan Beatsticks

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Wish Dragon 
- Wide Domain
- Half of a Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres or Moon of the Closed Heaven 
- Small Defensive Wall

Wish Dragon has the ability to tribute itself in order to summon 2 lv1 Dragon Tokens with no atk/def. This ability additionally locks us from summoning monsters from the extra deck, since we have no lv5 or higher Dragons in the Extra Deck. What this ability provides however, is a little defensive wall that our opponents will have to destroy before they can hurt our lifepoints. 

Wish Dragon is not the best monster in the game, however it does have a perfect domain for this type of deck - wide enough to reach most handtraps while still being easily summonable. Being normal summonable, we can combine it with any other monster in order to summon our powerful link-2s. 

Handtraps
- Negates
- Battle Faders
- Free Summons

Handtraps are the core of the deck, however due to reaching for quantity rather than quality, this deck suffers from many bad conditional and weak handtraps. Regardless however, a hand of 5 can expect to sample 3 handtraps from our pool, and with those 3 handtraps hopefully stop the most problematic combos. 

The goal of this deck is to handtrap and beat them up, so to that point, the player must be aware of the opponent's choke points so that after the handtrap they can never perform the combo again. The power of handtraps is their life in the hand rather than the field, making your opponent's boardbreakers ineffective in preventing you from stopping their combos. 

The Battle Faders of the deck help us stay alive - due to the nature of handtraps our field will be empty most times except for the 2 tokens that our deckmaster Wish Dragon provides. 
Remember that a lot of handtraps are also conditional on an empty field. 

PSY-Framegear monsters require a PSY-Frame Driver, but will banish the PSY-Frame Driver after use. To solve this problem, we play Primite Fusion and Branded Regained (with PSY-Framelord Lambda) to shuffle the PSY-Frame Driver back from banishment into deck. 
Bystial monsters are extremely powerful, especially in conjuction with The Bystial Lubellion ability to search Branded Regained to complete a stream of constant resource generation.  

Beatsticks
- Free Summon
- Clean up the board

Since our Deckmaster Wish Dragon does not provide much attack on their own, we resort to adding monsters in the Main Deck that can presssure our opponent's life points after we have caused them to fail their combos. This deck is rather low to the ground. 

These Beatsticks summon themselves for free, and thus can also be used as half of a Moon of the Closed Heaven for Fiendsmith lines. 
Fiendsmith is our most vaulable extra deck pieces due to thier recusrivibility. Fiendsmith's Rextremende is particularly high attack mosnter that can cause trouble for our opponents. Please note that Fiendsmith Engraver will not be able to discard itself from hand, due to the deck having no Fiendsmith spell/traps. 

Other Considerations: 

Handtraps: Supply Soldier of the Indestructible Insects , Conbirdable , Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended , Mahaama the Fairy Dragon , Herald of Orange Light 

Monsters: Chaos Dragon Levianeer , Fossil Dyna Pachycephalo , Hugin the Runick Wings , First of the Dragons , Regenesis Lord 

Deckmasters: Koa'ki Meiru Beetle , Justice of Prophecy , Propa Gandake 

The duels not over - it never began.

deck_excerpt: ALIN Ancient Fairy Dragon Support v2 list
deck_description:
I have been refining this deck since my last list. (If you're interested, here it is: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/luna-invoked-597401)

With a suggestion from the comment on my last list, (thank you TheDragon56) I have added Pot of Prosperity and Set Rotation.  These cards are natural additions to this deck and help consistency immensely.

Additionally, I have added Chicken Game as pretty much an Upstart Goblin that also sets field spell.  I have also added Multi-Universe, an insane card that fixes the main combo's issue of not being able to use Ancient Fairy Dragon's field spell pop without compromising Ancient Fairy Life Dragon's search.  Now, you can use AFD to pop World of Spirits, search Multi-Universe, and activate it to replace World of Spirits and giving it protection from backrow hate.  I also added Junk Speeder as a way to get to your level 8 bosses with Kuribon the Fairy Spirit and Regulus the Fairy Beast if Regulus's search gets interupted.  I added Black Rose Moonlight Dragon as another level 7 boss monster that you can go lv4 body + Revolution Synchron into.  I also cut down on a copy of Ancient Fairy Life Dragon as it doesn't come up as often as I'd like.

I also shifted around the non-engine to be more optimal.  I added Solemn Judgment over Solemn Strike because I feel having more counters to board breakers against your Eternal Sunshine and Ancient Fairy Life Dragon is more helpful for the gameplan.

Potential changes and additions we should look out for are:
1. Running a second Spore the Fairy Seed to deal with Bystials ruining your combo.
2. Synchro Rumble as revival and protection for your boss monsters. 
3. Potentially running Crimson Dragon.


I would love to hear all your thoughts and additions on the deck!

Cheers!

Step into a shadowy realm where ancient forests whisper secrets and cunning witches weave their enchantments! This isn't just a deck; it's a thrilling fairy tale spun from the threads of the White Forest and the wicked allure of the Sinful Spoils. Unleash a symphony of spellcasting with the Spellbook lineage, while the enigmatic White Forest monsters stalk the shadows, ready to pounce with unexpected power. Diabellze and her sinister sisters sow chaos, entwining their dark magic with the forest's ancient guardians. But beware! This idyllic woodland holds a darker edge. The forbidden power of the Sinful Spoils offers tantalizing shortcuts and devastating plays, tempting you to walk a perilous path. Will you succumb to their allure, or will the steadfast protectors of the White Forest guide you to victory? Unravel intricate combos that summon colossal dragons from the depths of the Extra Deck, including the majestic Azamina Moa Regina and the formidable Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying. Disrupt your opponent's strategies with well-timed negations and cunning traps, all while weaving a narrative of light and shadow on the dueling field. This deck isn't just about winning; it's about the story you tell with every card played. Are you ready to delve into the mysteries of the White Forest and embrace the power of the Sinful Spoils? Only the most cunning duelists will survive this enchanting and treacherous adventure!

Behold! This isn't your grandma's tea party... unless your grandma summons colossal dragons that warp reality! This Dragonmaid deck blends the adorable charm of hospitality with the ferocious power of draconic destruction. One moment you're tidying up with your Maidens, the next you're unleashing the chaos of Light and Darkness Dragon or banishing foes with the encroaching Bystials. Prepare for a whirlwind of transformations and strategic shifts. We juggle adorable daily duties with the earth-shattering might of Dragon's Mirror and the cunning of Branded magic. Summon your ultimate Dragonmaid Sheou to lock down the board, or unleash the devastating Light End and Dark End Dragons to obliterate your opponent's defenses. With the Bystials adding a disruptive edge and Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres providing crucial negates, this deck offers a unique blend of control and explosive power. Don't underestimate the cuteness – it's just a clever disguise for the draconic storm brewing within! Are you ready to serve up a side of pure annihilation?

Prepare to witness the fusion of raw power and insidious darkness! This isn't just a Cyber Dragon deck; it's a Kaiju-fueled, Cyberdark-infused engine of destruction, piloted by the regal Therion "King" Regulus. Unleash colossal Kaiju upon your opponent's strongest threats, then seamlessly pivot into a relentless barrage of Cyber Dragons, bolstered by the sinister Cyberdark arsenal. Imagine the satisfying crunch of Jizukiru devouring a problematic monster, paving the way for a devastating Cyberdark End Dragon or the explosive might of Cyber End Dragon. Utilize the cunning of Cyberdark Chimera to fuse with your banished Cyber Dragons, unleashing the multi-attacking fury of Chimeratech Rampage Dragon. But the shadows hold their own terrifying secrets. Cyberdark Realm and Cyberdark Inferno fuel a relentless search for your key Cyberdark monsters and spells, while Cyberdark Invasion can snatch victory from the jaws of defeat. With the strategic use of Clockwork Night, even your opponent's machines can become fuel for your Cyberdark ambitions. This deck isn't just about brute force; it's about calculated aggression and exploiting your opponent's weaknesses. Ash Blossom and Infinite Impermanence stand guard, while Pot of Desires and Cyber Emergency ensure your hand is always primed for action. So, are you ready to command the fusion of light and darkness? To obliterate your foes with Kaiju might and the relentless evolution of Cyber Dragons, all while wielding the shadowy power of the Cyberdarks? This deck offers a unique and thrilling path to victory – are you bold enough to take it?

Step into a realm where twilight meets oblivion! This isn't your grandma's Lightsworn – we've plunged into the abyss and emerged with a chaotic symphony of light and darkness. Unleash devastating dragons born from the very fabric of chaos, fueled by the relentless milling power of Lightsworn and the banishing might of Necroface. Witness: Judgment Day on Demand: The ultimate arbiter, Judgment Dragon, stands ready to cleanse the field in a flash of incandescent light. Chaotic Rebirth: Levianeer and The Chaos Creator rise from the banished, bringing forth overwhelming force. Dimension-Shifting Mayhem: Disrupt your opponent's strategies while fueling your own chaotic engine. Synchro Summons from the Shadows: Explode into powerful Synchro monsters like Chaos Angel and the formidable Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying. The Ever-Present Threat of Minerva: Multiple iterations of this Lightsworn prodigy ensure relentless draw power and explosive Extra Deck plays. This deck dances on the edge of control and chaos, offering a unique and exhilarating gameplay experience. Are you ready to embrace the duality and unleash the true power of light and shadow?

Prepare to ensnare your opponents in a web of cunning and deception! This isn't your garden-variety Traptrix deck; it's a venomous viper's nest where the innocent beauty of the Traptrix hides a sinister secret. We've twisted the classic trap strategy, injecting it with the ancient power of the Apophis and Anubis! Imagine your opponent confidently striding into your field, only to be ambushed not just by the treacherous Trap Holes and the alluring Traptrix, but by living traps that slither onto the field as formidable monsters! Embodiment of Apophis and Apophis the Swamp Deity blur the lines between trap and monster, catching your foe completely off guard. And when the scales truly tip, the formidable Anubis the Last Judge and Verdict of Anubis stand ready to deliver a swift and merciless judgment, punishing their every misstep. But the surprises don't end there! The shadowy influence of The Man with the Mark and the disruptive power of cards like Dominus Impulse and Dominus Purge add layers of control and disruption your opponent won't see coming. And for those moments when you need to strike from the shadows, the Extra Deck boasts not only the classic Traptrix powerhouses like Traptrix Sera and Traptrix Rafflesia, but also the colossal Divine Serpent Apophis and the ultimate dragonic threat, Five-Headed Dragon! This deck isn't just about setting traps; it's about crafting an intricate and unpredictable battlefield where your opponent's every move could be their last. Are you ready to unleash the ancient serpents and deliver a truly unforgettable trap experience?

Step into the grand, yet treacherous, Silver Castle! This isn't your average Labrynth build; we've twisted the opulent halls with the shadowy allure of Diabellstar and her Sinful Spoils. Lure your opponent into a web of disruptive traps and cunning hand traps, orchestrated by the elegant Lady and Lovely Labrynth. But beware, for this castle hides more than just welcome mats. Unleash the unexpected might of the Azamina family, morphing and evolving in the Extra Deck to deliver devastating blows and control the flow of battle. From the regal Moa Regina to the shadowy Mu Rcielago, their presence adds a unique and powerful dimension to the Labrynth strategy. Fool your foes with Metalfoes Fusion and the Sinful Spoils package, loading your Graveyard for explosive plays with Transaction Rollback and the ever-present threat of Eradicator Epidemic Virus. With Evenly Matched to reset the board and Infinite Impermanence to stifle your opponent's every move, you'll be the true master of this labyrinthine encounter. Prepare for a Labrynth experience unlike any other – where beauty and brutality intertwine, and the unexpected reigns supreme. Will you extend a Big Welcome, or will your opponent find themselves lost in the castle's intricate and deadly design?

deck_excerpt: Deck de Dark World – Domine as Sombras e Domine o Duelo!  O Dark World é um deck sombrio e poderoso que se aproveita do descarte de cards pa
deck_description:
Deck de Dark World – Domine as Sombras e Domine o Duelo!

O Dark World é um deck sombrio e poderoso que se aproveita do descarte de cards para desencadear efeitos devastadores. Originário do reino das trevas, esse arquétipo gira em torno de monstros que ganham efeitos quando descartados por efeito de card, seja da sua mão ou do deck, transformando um aparente revés em uma vantagem avassaladora.

Principais Estratégias:

  • Descarte Agressivo: Cards como "Broww, Huntsman of Dark World", "Snoww, Unlight of Dark World" e "Reino das Trevas" permitem recuperar recursos e acelerar seu jogo.

  • Controle e Pressão: Monstros como "Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World" retornam do Cemitério para destruir cards do oponente e gerar vantagem.

  • Combos Explosivos: Cards como "The Gates of Dark World" e "Dark World Dealings" aceleram seu engine, enquanto "Ceruli, Guru of Dark World" e "Sillva, Warlord of Dark World" causam estragos ao serem descartados pelo adversário.

Por Que Jogar Dark World?

✔ Recuperação de Recursos: Quanto mais você descarta, mais seu campo se fortalece.
✔ Versatilidade: Funciona bem em formatos como Tcg, Master Duel e Duel Links.
✔ Potencial de OTK: Com os combos certos, você pode eliminar o oponente em um único turno!

Se você gosta de um estilo de jogo agressivo e cheio de reviravoltas, o Dark World é a escolha perfeita! Domine as trevas e reduza seus adversários a pó!

Dark World – Onde o Descarte é Apenas o Começo da Sua Vitória!

This isn't your grandma's Harpie deck – it's a whirlwind of Simorgh synergy, soaring to new heights with the cunning of the Mist Valley and the relentless aggression of their winged allies. Weave through a storm of Harpie Ladies, each a vital piece in a symphony of destruction, while the enigmatic Simorghs manipulate the winds to summon colossal threats and disrupt your opponent's every move. From the explosive potential of "Harpie's Feather Duster" to the lockdown power of "Harpie's Feather Storm," this deck commands the skies. Utilize the search power of "Harpie Harpist" and "Harpie Perfumer" to assemble your avian armada, then launch into devastating combos with "Harpie Channeler" and "Elegant Egotist." The strategic placement of "Harpies' Hunting Ground" and "Elborz, the Sacred Lands of Simorgh" will keep your opponent on edge, while "Simorgh Onslaught" and "Dominus Impulse" pave the way for overwhelming board presence. But the true brilliance lies in the seamless integration of the Simorghs. "Simorgh, Bird of Bringing" and "Simorgh, Bird of Beginning" ensure consistent resource gathering, while "Simorgh, Bird of Perfection" and "Simorgh, Bird of Protection" offer crucial disruption and resilience. When the time is right, unleash the might of "Simorgh of Darkness" and "Simorgh, Lord of the Storm" to dominate the field. The Extra Deck is a flexible arsenal, ready to adapt to any challenge. "Cyber Slash Harpie Lady" provides swift removal and further strengthens your Harpie strategy, while the Rank 4 toolbox offers versatile options like "Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir" and "Lightning Chidori." For those game-ending pushes, "Accesscode Talker" stands ready to deliver the final blow, guided by the strategic prowess of "Harpie Conductor." This isn't just a deck; it's an aerial assault, a masterclass in resource management, and a testament to the combined might of the Harpies and the Simorghs. Soar above the competition and leave your opponents in the dust – the storm is coming!

Behold! A symphony of synergistic destruction where the relentless milling power of Lightsworn collides head-on with the modular might of the ABC Union monsters and the disruptive force of Therions! This isn't just a deck; it's a high-octane thrill ride where Judgement Dragon's cataclysmic blast can clear the path for the combined arms assault of ABC-Dragon Buster and the strategic prowess of Therion "King" Regulus. Harness the speed of Galaxy Soldier and the graveyard manipulation of Starliege Seyfert to turbocharge your plays, while Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Infinite Impermanence stand guard against your opponent's schemes. Union Hangar and Union Activation ensure your ABC pieces are always within reach, ready to combine into their ultimate form. And when the situation calls for it, the Cyber Dragon package offers a technological edge, culminating in the fearsome Cyber Dragon Infinity. Dive into the chaos where Lightsworn's random destiny fuels a calculated engine of fusion and Xyz summons. Will you unleash the devastating XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon, the negation power of Invoked Mechaba, or the banishing brilliance of Michael, the Arch-Lightsworn? This deck demands a daring pilot, one who can navigate the delicate balance between self-milling and strategic deployment to seize victory from the jaws of chance!

The little French doll was a dear little doll

Tricked out in the sweetest of dresses;

Her eyes were of hue

A most delicate blue

And dark as the night were her tresses;

Her dear little mouth was fluted and red,

And this little French doll was so very well bred

That whenever accosted her little mouth said

"Mamma! mamma!"

 

The stockinet doll, with one arm and one leg,

Had once been a handsome young fellow;

But now he appeared

Rather frowzy and bleared

In his torn regimentals of yellow;

Yet his heart gave a curious thump as he lay

In the little toy cart near the window one day

And heard the sweet voice of that French dolly say:

"Mamma! mamma!"

 

He listened so long and he listened so hard

That anon he grew ever so tender,

For it's everywhere known

That the feminine tone

Gets away with all masculine gender!

He up and he wooed her with soldierly zest

But all she'd reply to the love he professed

Were these plaintive words (which perhaps you have guessed):

"Mamma! mamma!"

 

Her mother - a sweet little lady of five -

Vouchsafed her parental protection,

And although stockinet

Wasn't blue-blooded, yet

She really could make no objection!

So soldier and dolly were wedded one day,

And a moment ago, as I journeyed that way,

I'm sure that I heard a wee baby voice say:

"Mamma! mamma!"

deck_excerpt: Looks like Rabby has finally found some new friends!
deck_description:
This is a really fun (and surprisingly competent in my opinion) control deck I've cooked up after playing a Melffy/Beast control deck for a bit in the N/R tryout. The main idea is to solve the lack of an in-archetype normal summon for Melffy with the Primite engine, with Melffy Rabby being the card which bridges the two archetypes. It's a very grindy deck, which focuses on outresourcing the opponent over multiple turns (kinda like Paleozoic).

There is a video attached with some replays that better showcase how this deck works in action (I recommend you check it out!), but I'll give you an explanation right here as well.

If you don't know anything about Melffy, they are mostly Lvl 2 EARTH Beast monsters, with 0-400 ATK/DEF. These little creatures come out to play in the End Phase, where you Special Summon them from the hand. Then, when your opponent summons their big scary monsters, they hide, going back to your hand, and granting you some kind of advantage in the process:

  • Melffy Wally is generally the best to start with, summoning 2 other Melffys from the deck.
  • Melffy Puppy summons a Lvl 2 or lower Beast monster from the deck, which can be Wally (if you need more names), another Melffy, or any other tech card you might want to include. Most likely, you'll be summoning Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest a lot.
  • Melffy Catty adds any Beast monster from your deck to your hand. It can be Melffy Pinny or Hop Ear Squadron for Synchro plays, Melffy Rabby to turn on Primite Drillbeam, or even Alpha, the Master of Beasts if you need a big beatstick/board breaker.
  • Melffy Pony adds a Lvl 2 or lower Beast monster from the GY, being extremely important for the grind game.
  • Melffy Fenny summons any Beast monster from the hand. It might not seem that much, but many times you already searched or added back from GY everything you want and need a way to summon them from the hand (especially Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest), this solves that while also being another Melffy name.

Melffy Pinny works differently. It's a WATER Beast Tuner monster, which instead of going back to the hand, actually comes out to the field and then Synchro Summons using the Melffy monsters in your hand, giving you access to powerful Synchros, such as the in-archetype Merry Melffys, as well as Herald of the Arc Light, Silvera, Wolf Tamer of the White Forest or lines with Desert Locusts and Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon that can make a (temporarily unnafected) Baronne de Fleur. Hop Ear Squadron can also help with Synchro Summoning, but takes a monster from the field instead, and only works during the opponent's main phase, so it's a bit more limited (still very useful to have though).

Melffy also have 2 Xyz Monsters, both very useful:

  • Melffy of the Forest searches any Melffy card, and is a monster negate, albeit a slow one. You could play some Rank 2 engine to make this on the first turn, like Deep Sea Diva (or Nimble Beaver, which would be better if it was unlimited already...), but I didn't want more normal summons.
  • Joyous Melffys can make Melffys attack directly (including itself, so may be useful for ZEUS if you're not locked) and can revive Lvl 2 or lower Beast monsters from the GY during your opponent's turn, being extremely important to setup using Rescue Cat / Obedience Schooled since the monsters used will come back with their effects online.

Rescue Cat is a good normal summon (finally I can make use of my royal copy lol), you can summon 2 Melffy monsters from the deck and then make Spright Elf, which can summon them both back (one during your turn, another during your opponent's turn) with their effects online and also protected from targeting (Imperm can be a problem sometimes...).

Obedience Schooled is another great starter (doesn't use your Normal Summon, which means you can use it on the Primite), which summons 3 Lvl 2 or lower Beasts from the deck, but locks you into only Special Summoning Beast monsters for the rest of the turn, so you'll probably go for Joyous Melffys instead, which can summon them all back (with their effects of course) during your opponent's turn. Melffy of the Forest is also an option, but it's weaker in my opinion, since cards like Ash, Veiler and Imperm can ruin your day, while Joyous Melffys is a bit harder to interact with - since it is a quick effect, if your opponent targets it you can dodge and summon everything back, and if they don't you wait until they put a card on the field to play around Imperm.

Then we have Melffy Rabby, a vanilla. Normally not played in Melffy, but with the release of the Primite cards it opens up a different way to play this deck, which I don't see many people talk about online. We have an archetype with no Normal Summon (requiring us to use more generic options like Rescue Cat) but with an easily accessible Normal monster - this screams "Primite!" to me. We can use Primite Dragon Ether Beryl as our normal summon (even after using Obedience Schooled) to get access to Primite Drillbeam, which is an extremely powerful card that keeps coming back every turn, as long as you have access to Ether Beryl. There are also some other synergies, like Primite Lordly Lode summoning Melffy Rabby (both to turn on Primite Drillbeam and making Ether Beryl a 1-card Spright Elf to give target protection to your other Melffys), or Ether Beryl being a Lvl 4 monster that can combine with Hop Ear Squadron for some Synchro plays.

The side deck includes some cards that you could consider:

  • Satellite Warrior is something you want to include in your Extra Deck, it is extremely good to make in the Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon lines, I just didn't have any more UR points. Play it if you can.
  • Evenly Matched isn't bad in this deck for going 2nd, since this is a slow deck you can afford to lose a battle phase if that means you can get control of the game. Unfortunately, it alone doesn't work very well, since most decks can put up at least 1 omni-negate (you'd need Evenly plus a way to bait omni-negates, or multiple copies of Evenly). Maybe it would work better if you pair it with other board breakers, such as Forbidden Droplet, but I ended up switching it for Nibiru, the Primal Being (Nibiru's utility is also questionable at times, but since your Melffys go back to the hand, even going 1st you can tribute only your opponent's board).
  • Deep Sea Diva could be a Rank 2 engine to make Melffy of the Forest and get a Melffy name, such as Melffy Wally. If playing pure this would be the way to go, but I am playing Primite Dragon Ether Beryl and Rescue Cat and I don't want too many Normal Summons.
  • A 2nd copy of Alpha, the Master of Beasts wouldn't be terrible, it's a decent card and it was useful during my climb, but it is bad to draw going 1st.
  • White Steed of the Floral Knights could have some applications, such as making Spright Elf with it + any Melffy name that you normal summon, or going directly into Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon with Hop Ear Squadron, while also being battle protection in the GY. I've never tried it though, maybe there's even more that I'm not seeing.
  • Royal Rhino with Deceitful Dice is just a funny tech I've played in the N/R tryout. It is summonable by Melffy Puppy, it's not the best of course but you could play it if you want a laugh or two.

I was able to climb from Diamond V to Master V with this list, and I feel like I would've been able to climb higher if I played more (I also want to try out other decks though). If you're still reading, you're probably interested in this concept, so I hope I can hear your thoughts about it! Also, if you try it out, let me know how it went, I'd love to see someone reach Master I with it :)
Z-arc go brrr!

deck_excerpt: Ruin is a craft, War is the kiln
deck_description:
Cute Play. Here's why it doesn't matter. 
Evilswarm Exciton Knight and boardbreakers combine to erase your opponents' boards—and their recovery.

Deckmaster: Magical Musketeer Starfire 
Domain Restriction: LIGHT // FIEND
Made for Domain Format

Join the Community Discord: https://discord.gg/3jRnBGHQJs 

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Catagories:

This strategy builds upon 3 simple strategies:

  • Neutralize
  • Remove
  • Eliminate

That is why the deck is 90% boardbreakers.

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Magical Musketeer Starfire 
- Summon out a lv4 from deck to make Evilswarm Exciton Knight 
- LIGHT//FIEND to make Fiendsmith's Requiem and/or Magical Musketeer Max 

Magical Musketeer Starfire is a powerful Magical Musketeer monster that can be summon out Magical Musketeer Calamity if we activate a boardbreaker in the same column as she is in. After using her effect, you can make Magical Musketeer Max in order to accue more resources, and resummon her from GY using Magical Musketeer Calamity.  This boost of resources is useful to have more boardbreakers while still maintaining the 2 LIGHT//FIEND necessiary to create a Evilswarm Exciton Knight and wipe the board. 

Magical Musketeer Max adds: 

  • Magical Musket - Cross-********** 
  • Magical Musket - Desperado 
  • Magical Musket - Last Stand 

Magical Musketeer Starfire summons:

  • Magical Musketeer Calamity 
  • Magical Musketeer Caspar 
  • Magical Musketeer Doc 
  • Magical Musketeer Wild 

The additional influx of LIGHT//FIEND into our GY allows us to more freely use Fiendsmith's Sequence to fusion summon Fiendsmith's Desirae with. The most ideal situation will be using Fiendsmith's Sequence to summon Fiendsmith's Desirae while still maintaining an Fiendsmith Engraver and Lacrima the Crimson Tears in the GY.
Combo:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-71140535 

What is this deck's combos?
- Use Fiendsmith engine recursivly!
- Use Magical Musketeer Starfire to make Evilswarm Exciton Knight! 
- Hit them hard with an Fiendsmith's Agnumday equipped to Fiendsmith's Desirae! 
- Outgrind, outfight your opponent and set up an unaffected towers in Fiendsmith's Rextremende! 

While most of the deck are individually powerful boardbreakers, this deck makes use of the Fiendsmith engine in order to have a recurring monster engine. Here is the short combo:

Fiendsmith's Sanct or Archfiend Eccentrick one-card combos:

  • Fiendsmith's Desirae combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67570995 
  • D/D/D Wave High King Caesar combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67571184 

These combos are weaker than having a non-pendulum Light Fiend monster as a starter. You lose out on the ablility to have Lacrima the Crimson Tears + Fiendsmith's Requiem , which at baseline is a free monster and at ceiling can send Fiendsmith in Paradise (sending Fiendsmith's Desirae) for another interruption.

Lacrima the Crimson Tears one-card combos:

  • Fiendsmith's Desirae combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67581722 
  • D/D/D Wave High King Caesar combo: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-67581536

Lacrima the Crimson Tears with Fiendsmith Engraver allows us to have an interrupt through Fiendsmith in Paradise sending Fiendsmith's Desirae. This makes Lacrima the Crimson Tears hard to handtrap because they would need to negate both the on field effect and the GY effect (after Fiendsmith's Requiem is made). 

Fiendsmith's Sequence Fusion Summon (by shuffling back from GY):

  • Fiendsmith's Desirae: Most common, provides negates
  • Fiendsmith's Rextremende: Unaffected monster, useful when we wish to use boardwipes without losing our own monsters. Can also be summoned to recycle Runick Fusion monsters to the Extra Deck. 
  • The Duke of Demise: Used to recycle D/D/D Wave High King Caesar, Necroquip Princess, Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis, Chaos Angel back into the Extra Deck     
  • The Duke of Demise: Additional Normal Summon resummons Magical Musketeer Starfire, linking The Duke of Demise with Fiendsmith's Sequence for Fiendsmith's Agnumday to revive another lv4 LIGHT//FIEND to make Evilswarm Exciton Knight again with the lv4 and Magical Musketeer Starfire.  

Boardbreaking
- Destroy all of your opponent's monster negates
- Setup a situation to use Evilswarm Exciton Knight to destroy the field of Spell/Traps and Defensive monsters

Due to a desire to play a high density of Boardbreakers, we have scrapped the bottom of the barrel. Some of our boardbreakers will be more costly and less effective than others.

This deck is setup to specifically deal with monster-heavy boards, and will not do well against decks that setup negation in the Spell/Trap Zone. The primary goal is to deal with your opponent's endboards all at once thorugh Evilswarm Exciton Knight, which can be used multiple times if needed. 

Evilswarm Exciton Knight is extremely important because it is a boardwipe to all 3 opponent's fields. In addition, as a LIGHT//FIEND it can start the Fiendsmith's Requiem combo, and as an XYZ monster it can be used to summon Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder in case the fieldwipe failed. Keep in mind that Evilswarm Exciton Knight has no Once-Per-Turn and can be recycled into the Extra Deck using Fiendsmith Engraver.    

After clearing the boardstate, we will wish to lean on the Fiendsmith cards to keep us in the game. This is due to our Boardbreakers all being one-time use - after breaking the board once our hand will be exhasted.

A note on lack of Spell/Trap Removal: 
The most common set cards in Domain Format are boardwipes like Torrential Tribute , Needle Ceiling , and Book of Eclipse. While these cards can stop us from setting up Evilswarm Exciton Knight if they resolve, they also just do the job of Evilswarm Exciton Knight, so this deck's stretegy does not mind them too much. Outside of that, other common Spell/Traps are advantage generating s/t and Floodgates, neither of which this deck minds. Evilswarm Exciton Knight can destroy the Advantage generating S/T, and this deck plays so low to the ground that Floodgates hardly harm it. The most worrysome set card is negation. We will simply just need to play through the negation. 
By disregarding Spell/Trap Removal, we more increase our chance of having a hand that can deal with 3 monster boards - a tough ask by itself. 

Other Considerations:

Spell Speed Boardbreakers: Vesper Girsu , Flash of the Forbidden Spell , Xyz Import , That Wacky Alchemy! , Share the Pain , Dark Core , Parallel Twister 
Spells/Traps: Runick cards, Fiendsmith's Sanct , Torrential Tribute , Kyoutou Waterfront , Terraforming , Pot of Desires 

Monsters: Lava Golem , The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode , Archfiend Eccentrick , Constellar Ptolemy M7 (recycles Zeus)

Other Variants:

Trap Heavy: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/fiendsmith-runick-paleo-558811 
LiveTwins: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/fiendsmith-live-twins-601324 

Recap

Important Cards: Evilswarm Exciton Knight , Fiendsmith's Requiem , Lacrima the Crimson Tears 
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Destroy them and watch them flounder.

Built to Unbuild, Shaped to Unshape.

Step right up, duelists, and behold a spectacle of chaotic synergy! This isn't just a deck; it's a whirlwind of mischievous Fiendsmiths and cryptic Fabled monsters, a symphony of discards and summons that will leave your opponent bewildered and buried under an avalanche of unexpected plays. We're not just playing cards; we're conducting a ritual of rapid-fire combos, fueled by the forbidden knowledge of Dark World Dealings and the explosive potential of Fiendsmith's Tract. Witness the arcane artistry of Lacrima the Crimson Tears, rising from the ashes of discarded dreams, while the enigmatic Fabled Raven whispers secrets that unlock devastating Extra Deck threats like the colossal Fiendsmith's Rextremende and the alluring Fiendsmith's Desirae. Brace yourself for the unpredictable power of Mulcharmy Fuwalos, threatening to erupt into a field-flooding nightmare, and the cunning disruption of Droll & Lock Bird, slamming the brakes on your opponent's best-laid plans. This isn't a deck for the faint of heart. It demands a daring duelist, one who revels in risk and masters the art of controlled chaos. Can you harness the volatile fusion of Fiendsmith ingenuity and Fabled sorcery to unleash a torrent of relentless attacks and outwit your foes with mind-bending plays? Enter the Fabled Forge, where victory is forged in the fires of discard and the echoes of laughter!

An "Eldlich" Deck that fights tenaciously with Trap Cards.
Based around "Eldlich the Golden Lord", "Eldlixir" cards can Summon monsters, and "Golden Land" cards can act as interference.
Get a good grasp of these effects to ensure you combine them effectively! Be careful not to Set or activate cards recklessly.

Prepare to witness a symphony of steel and starlight! This isn't just a deck; it's a high-octane narrative where the relentless march of the Centur-Ions collides with the shadowy intrigue of the Orcusts, all orchestrated by the regal command of Therion "King" Regulus. Weaving through the chaos are the forbidden whispers of World Legacy, ensuring every move is a calculated risk, a thrilling gamble on the edge of oblivion. Unleash devastating combos that pivot from the explosive power of Centur-Ion's Level Modulation to the dark recursion of the Orcust engine. Summon colossal Link monsters like the majestic Centur-Ion Legatia and the formidable Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star, each a harbinger of your opponent's impending doom. But beware, for this symphony is not without its dissonant chords. Navigate the treacherous allure of darkness and the unpredictable draw power of Pot of Desires, knowing that every card drawn could be the key to victory or the prelude to your downfall. Disrupt your opponent's strategies with the spectral grace of Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and the inescapable negation of Infinite Impermanence. This deck isn't just about playing cards; it's about crafting a thrilling saga of strategic brilliance and calculated aggression. Will you master the intricate dance between these powerful archetypes and ascend to victory, or will you become another forgotten note in the grand orchestra of duels? Only the bravest and most cunning duelists dare to find out!

deck_excerpt: Play through entire boards and every handtrap with Branded Despia! Still is the most reliable fusion deck to climb Masterduel ladder with!
deck_description:
Does your opponent have several negates, interruptions, handtraps and they activated Maxx "C" during the Draw Phase? No problem! Albaz and friends are unstoppable! Three years of Branded in Masterduel hasn't slowed down this strategy at all!

From my experience, Albaz and friends have been one of the most reliably powerful and usable decks I've used in the two years the strategy was legal in Masterduel. Branded Despia is also near its full power in Masterduel, making it an extremely powerful choice of strategy to tackle Masterduel ladder!

Saronir, Opening and Aluber are now all back to 3 when in the past, they were previously only at 1. Now all they have to do at Konami is make Branded Fusion 3 and Albaz will dominate in a format that is full of massive negate boards and Mulcharmy/Maxx "C" handtraps.

In my humble opinion, this makes Branded the current strongest fusion deck on ladder, able to go first making complex, multilayered interruptions. Going second, Branded has enough momentum, in-engine power and boardbreakers to plow through massive boards with multiple negates! Albaz and friends are up next as Yugioh's featured anime character (after Sky Striker Raye of course), and their banlist treatment of Branded Despia are definitely evidence of that! I'll be looking forward to the insane "season 2" support Albaz gets. In the meantime, let's fuse our way to the top of ladder!

If you want a thorough guide on this deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

Creator: Jalon Flores

Tournament: Los Angeles WCQ Regional – May 10th 2025

Placement: 1st Place
Memento done right
https://youtu.be/NAxucTvIpKM?feature=shared
Rank 4 monster spam
EXPLOSION!

I have actually had this Decklist for a while, but I really was just waiting to see if there was going to be any more support being revealed for Magistus. As seen with the OCG Stories Sky Striker support, they got so much support pretty consistently, even till now. So, I was just kinda waiting to see if there was going to be any insane Magistus support dropping so that I wouldn’t have to constantly revisit this Deck. That was not the case, but this support really is 70% good to 30% decent so far. Spoon, the Seal of Magistus is insane since it is both a searcher in the hand who can also banish itself from GY to equip a Magistus monster from GY or Extra Deck. Zoroa, the Magistus Victorious Verethragna is really good interruption and removal on both players’ turns. Endymion, the Crescent of Magistus works really well with their other new piece of support Crowley, the Gifted of Magistus which gives you access to the Invoked Fusions since it is treated as Aleister the Invoker when being used from face-up field as Fusion Material. And with the new Endymion, you can basically access either the Magistus or Invoked Fusions on your opponent’s turn. Magia Magic - Thor Hammer is more of an Endymion card than a Magistus card, but it is searchable in both Decks and is probably at the very most played at 1 copy if people choose to do so. Verre Magic - Lacrima of Light is literally insane, especially for Witchcrafter since it dumps a Spellcaster monster or a Spell/Trap from Deck or it can get you to the new Crowley which gives Witchcrafter access to the Invoked Fusions. And then we got Invoked Magistus Omega which is not awful, but it is certainly not as good for interruption or removal as the new Zoroa Fusion or even Invoked Augoeides even if it can float. 

However, the most important card among these is Crowley, the Gifted of Magistus. Besides being treated as Aleister when used from face-up field as Fusion Material, it can Special Summon itself from hand if it was added to hand other than by drawing it. So, adding him from Deck, GY, banishment, or bouncing him from field back to hand will trigger this. Also, if he is Normal or Special Summoned, you can Fusion Summon an Invoked or Magistus Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck using materials from hand and/or field, which means that we will be able to access the Level 9 Invoked Mechaba. It’s been a while since I’ve talked about Invoked Prediction Princess, so as a refresher, Invoked Mechaba is a Level 9 LIGHT Machine Fusion Monster that requires Aleister the Invoker and a LIGHT monster as Fusion Material and as a soft once per turn, when a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect is activated, you can Quick Effect send the same type of card (Monster, Spell, Trap) from your hand to the GY to negate the activation and banish that card. Not only is Mechaba a Level 9 monster that gives you the opportunity to use World Legacy Monstrosity, but if you manage to get it out on your opponent’s turn, that is another point of interaction or even a form of protection for you to utilize. This Deck is Magistus Prediction Princess, and if anything, it is a better version of Invoked Prediction Princess for the sole reason that you can Fusion Summon on your opponent’s turn for a Mechaba or the new Zoroa. 

Full combo is either Spoon, the Seal of Magistus + World Legacy Monstrosity or Rilliona, the Magistus of Verre + Monstrosity. Given Spoon and Monstrosity, activate Spoon and discard it to add Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame from your Deck to your hand. Normal Summon Zoroa and activate its effect to equip Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden from your Extra Deck to him. Zoroa triggers upon being equipped to Special Summon Spoon from GY with its effects negated. Activate Artemis’s effect to add Crowley, the Gifted of Magistus from Deck to hand. Crowley activates upon being added to Special Summon himself and on Special Summon, use his effect to Fusion Summon Invoked Mechaba. Activate Monstrosity targeting Mechaba to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Mechaba and Deus-X into Mereologic Aggregator who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY which triggers it in GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Aggregator activates its other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and reattaching Herald from GY. Link Aggregator and Zoroa into Endymion, the Crescent of Magistus. Chain Link 1 Herald in GY and Chain Link 2 Endymion on field. Endymion equips Crowley from GY to itself and Herald searches for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Activate Underworld Ritual of Prediction tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotrei. Bibliomuse triggers in GY to Special Summon herself back face-down. Tarotrei activates targeting and flipping Bibliomuse face-up which triggers Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect which searches Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual. Underworld Ritual again tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-up. End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons Deus-X from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and then you can then use Tarotreith’s effect to flip both Bibliomuse and Deus-X face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for another Tarotrei and another Underworld Ritual. Now, you have follow-up in hand, Tarotrei can Quick Effect book a monster on field, Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s field, Bibliomuse is protecting Tarotrei and Tarotreith from targeting and destruction, and Endymion can bounce Crowley to hand which triggers him to Special Summon himself from hand and then Fusion Summon another Mechaba or Zoroa, the Magistus Victorious Verethragna. 

Now, if you want to go through the Rilliona line, you don’t need to open with Spoon. You can just Normal Summon Rilliona. On Normal Summon, Rilliona searches for Magistus Theurgy from Deck. Activate Theurgy targeting Rilliona to equip Artemis to her from Extra Deck. Artemis activates to search for Crowley who then Special Summons itself from hand and Fusion Summons Mechaba using itself and Rilliona. Activate Monstrosity targeting Mechaba and it’s the same line from there. However, you do not have the additional body to make Endymion, so just Xyz Summon Aggregator into the EMZ and then once you do the Herald stuff with it, Link it off into Gravity Controller. Also, make sure to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down since we don’t have access to Endymion bounce Crowley and then Crowley Special Summons himself from hand on our opponent’s turn. We can flip Tarotreith face-up on our opponent’s turn to get a Pot of the Forbidden from our Deck and then use that as interruption instead.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. If you do not want to play the Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity and the Rilliona, the Wondrous Magistus Witch Wardrobe (I really thought this name looks really long, but it still loses to Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Evening Twilight and D/D/D/D Super-Dimensional Sovereign Emperor Zero Paradox) in the Extra Deck, you can also consider playing Summoner of Illusions and still be able to access either Mechaba or the Zoroa Fusion through the Rilliona line. For the Magistus Monsters: 1 Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame, 3 Rilliona, the Magistus of Verre, 3 Spoon, the Seal of Magistus, and 2 Crowley, the Gifted of Magistus. Zoroa can target a Magistus you control to equip it with a Magistus from Extra Deck, and if it becomes equipped with a Magistus Monster Card, you can Special Summon a Level 4 Spellcaster from hand or GY (other than another copy of itself) in Defense with its effects negated. Zoroa is not a bad card. In fact, it is one of the better Main Deck Magistus cards. However, in this Deck specifically, it is best to search him off of Spoon rather than hard drawing him. It’s fine if we do hard draw him, but we just need to also draw a LIGHT monster to make up for the fact that we didn’t have Spoon. Crowley would then make Mechaba using itself and the LIGHT monster we drew in our hand. Rilliona on Normal or Special Summon can either add a Magistus Spell/Trap from Deck to hand or return a banished Level 4 or lower Spellcaster to GY. You can also banish her from GY and target a Magistus you control to equip it with a Magistus from GY except for a Level 4 monster. We are mainly just using her to search for a Magistus Spell/Trap, primarily Magistus Theurgy. But her second effect can come up on a following turn if Spoon is not in GY. Her GY effect is basically a heavily watered down version of Spoon’s GY effect. You can discard Spoon from hand to either search for a Magistus monster from Deck other than Spoon or you can halve the ATK of a face-up monster your opponent controls until the end of the turn. Also, you can banish Spoon from GY to target a face-up monster you control and equip it with a Magistus monster from Extra Deck or GY. Spoon is obviously a very good searcher, but let’s talk about that GY effect. Unlike pretty much all the other Magistus cards other than Aiwass (I guess), Spoon can equip a Magistus monster from Extra Deck or GY to any monster you control, so any monster you control can make use of the Magistus monster’s equip effects. Let’s go through them. Aiwass, the Magistus Spell Spirit gives the equipped monster 1000 ATK/DEF. Vahram, the Magistus Divinity Dragon makes the equipped monster unable to be destroyed by your opponent’s Spell/Trap effects and it allows the equipped monster to destroy the monster it battles at the start of the damage step. Ninaruru, the Magistus Glass Goddess allows the monster to make up to 2 attacks on monsters during the Battle Phase and while Ninaruru is equipped, it can target a Magistus card in your Spell/Trap Zone and a Spell/Trap your opponent controls and destroy both. Rilliona, the Wondrous Magistus Witch Wardrobe, while equipped to a monster, can target an Effect Monster your opponent controls and negate its effects until the end of the turn. Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden, while equipped to a monster, can add a Magistus monster from Deck to hand. Aiwass in general is good for interruption, but boosting a monster by 1000/1000 when equipped is not that useful. Vahram is pretty specific in what it can be used to help out against. It’s not like it makes the equipped monster unaffected by your opponent’s Spell/Trap effects, and destroying a monster at the start of damage calculation is not too useful in a Deck with a lot of high ATK monsters. If anything, it works better when equipped to a monster that’s equipped with multiple Magistus monsters to maximize its benefits. Ninaruru is pretty good, but I’d rather side it in when I know that I am going second or if I really need Spell/Trap destruction since our Extra Deck has realistically 2-3 replaceable cards. Rilliona is also pretty good. Shame that she is not a Quick Effect, but that would be pushing it. Although she is still good as a way to deal with monster effects on a following turn or going second (sort of). As for Artemis, we are already playing her, but on a following turn, you can use Spoon to equip Artemis to a random monster and then search for Crowley who Special Summons himself and Fusion Summons an Invoked or Magistus Fusion Monster. That’s really good. Moving on, I already explained what Crowley does at the beginning of this, but we are playing 2 because I fear God and so that we can do the thing I just described with Artemis. Next, we have 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Effect Veiler. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. I wish there was a way to search this card in this Deck, but because Magistus monsters are a 4-axis Deck, it’s not like we can consistently put a Level 1 on the field to make Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. 1 Magistus Theurgy which targets a Magistus you control to equip it with a Magistus from your Extra Deck, GY, or face-up field except for a Level 4 monster. But if you have at least 1 each of a Magistus Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, and Link Monster in your Gy, you can equip it with a non-Magistus Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, or Link from your Extra Deck instead. This card is what you are primarily searching off of Rilliona to do your combo. But we are also playing 1 Magistus Vritra which targets a Level 4 or lower Magistus in GY and Special Summons it. Also, if a Magistus card(s) in your Spell/Trap Zones would be destroyed by your opponent’s card effect, you can banish it from GY instead. So, if you draw Theurgy, you can still search this off of Rilliona and then you will be able to end on an Endymion, the Crescent of Magistus equipped with a Crowley like if you went through the Spoon into Zoroa line. 1 Pot of Prosperity and 1 Called by the Grave. 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 2 Invoked Mechaba. 1 Zoroa, the Magistus Victorious Verethragna which requires a Magistus and a Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, or Link as Fusion Material. It can target an Effect Monster your opponent controls or in your GY and equip that monster to itself. And when a monster effect is activated, it can Quick Effect send a face-up Magistus Monster Card you control to the GY to negate that effect and then you can destroy 1 card your opponent controls. Really good effect being able to negate an activated monster effect and then destroy that card if it was on field or another card your opponent controls. 1 Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity which requires a Spellcaster Tuner and 1+ non-Tuners as material. On Synchro Summon, it can equip a Magistus monster from your Extra Deck to itself. And while it is face-up on the field, your opponent cannot activate the effects of monsters with the same card type as the Magistus Monster Cards in your Spell/Trap Zone (Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, Link). Also, if it is in the GY, you can target a Magistus card you control and destroy it to Special Summon Zoroa back. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Rilliona, the Wondrous Magistus Witch Wardrobe which is to be either used with the Synchro Zoroa or with Spoon as mentioned previously. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Endymion, the Crescent of Magistus. On Link Summon, he can target a Magistus you control and equip a Spellcaster from your GY or banishment to it. And during the Main Phase, as a Quick Effect, he can target a Spellcaster Monster Card in your Spell/Trap Zone that’s treated as an Equip Spell and return it to hand. Notably, these effects are 1 effect per turn and only once that turn. 1 Gravity Controller. 1 Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden. 

Side Deck: 1 Aiwass, the Magistus Spell Spirit which requires a Magistus and a Spellcaster as Fusion Material. While its an Equip Card, the equipped monster gains 1000 ATK/DEF and during the Main Phase, you can Quick Effect target 1 other face-up monster on the field and equip it to that monster. And while it is equipped to an opponent’s monster, you take control of that monster but it cannot activate its effects. Aiwass is just an alternative Fusion Monster you can make with Crowley on your opponent’s turn or something you can play instead of Synchro Zoroa if you choose to play Summoner of Illusions and want more Fusion Monster options. 1 Vahram, the Magistus Divinity Dragon and 1 Ninaruru, the Magistus Glass Goddess. Vahram is for scenarios where you want to equip a Synchro Monster to Synchro Zoroa or IDK if you want to protect your Tarotrei from Lightning Storm? Ninaruru has more usage since it can make a monster its equipped to (via Spoon’s effect) into a double attacker and as Spell/Trap removal. 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Droll & Lock Bird, 3 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_description:
6th place Esher Regional finish

 

Piloted by Nalin Gunawardena (Zaio Volnutt)

Playing style[edit]

They are similar to the "Dark World" archetype in that the Monsters thrive off of effects that discard; however, unlike Dark World, all "Fabled" Monsters will benefit off of any discard, even for cost. Even though cards like "Dark World Dealings" can be used with "Fabled" monsters, it's best to keep a high monster count, and use their own effects to Special Summon them. The archetype also greatly benefits from cards like "Tour Guide From the Underworld", which gets "Kushano" to the grave as quick as possible, and sets up for Rank 3 Xyz Monsters, such as "Leviair the Sea Dragon". Though these Xyz support the deck, the main focus is Synchros, such as "Fabled Ragin", "Formula Synchron" and "T.G. Hyper Librarian", in order to maintain the card advantage lost by summoning those monsters. "Fabled" Decks can be very versatile. Because of their potential to abuse special summons and also being a LIGHT Fiend archetype, there are a lot of cards to support them. The key to a successful Deck is to control the field while slowly gaining advantage for powerful finish. "Beckoning Light" is by far the best tool in "Fabled" arsenal. It lets you discard your Fabled monsters while getting another ones from your Graveyard. Both "Phoenix Wing Wind Blast" and "Raigeki Break" are really handy for this deck, letting you to disrupt your opponent's plays and discard a "Fabled" Monsters. By combining them with "The Fabled Catsith", you get a powerful removal tool. Another way around is to add T.G engine ("T.G. Warwolf" and "T.G. Striker") and focus on a Beast support (like "Horn of the Phantom Beast") to make a good use of The Fabled sub-series. With the changes brought by Link Monsters and Master Rule 4, the sheer swarming ability of this archetype allows for rapid Link and Synchro summons. As time goes on more Link monsters will be printed that indirectly support "Fabled" cards.

deck_excerpt: Red eyes black dragon Allure Queen Kashtira
deck_description: Red eyes black dragon Allure Queen Kashtira

Enter a captivating world where spellcasting ingenuity intertwines with strategic brilliance! This Witchcrafter deck is more than just a collection of cards; it's a carefully constructed ensemble of magical artisans, ready to weave a tapestry of control and triumph.

Witness the delightful synergy of the Witchcrafter sisters, each a vital component in a wondrous workshop of spell manipulation. From the resourceful Schmietta to the commanding Madame Verre, their enchanting abilities work in perfect concert, recycling your magical tools and disrupting your opponent's carefully laid plans.

But the intrigue deepens with the introduction of potent and unusual magic. Time-Tearing Morganite and Succumbing-Song Morganite bend the flow of the duel, enabling surprising plays and unexpected advantages. Guilt Gripping Morganite adds a strategic edge, deterring your opponent from challenging your mystical command.

And then, legendary forces emerge! The Gaze of Timaeus unlocks the formidable might of Timaeus the United Magidragon, Dark Magician the Dragon Knight, and Dark Magician of Destruction, infusing your spell-based strategy with draconic power. The iconic Dark Magicians stand united, a testament to the enduring strength of magical alliances.

Prepare for a duel where whimsical charm meets strategic depth, where spell counters fuel legendary dragons, and where each card drawn contributes to a grand spectacle of magical mastery. This isn't just a deck; it's an enchanting narrative waiting to be written!

So this is my approach on the branded deck. I'm playing only the bystials that I have , if you dont want any bystials play maybe something from the "side tech" that isnt that expensive. Part of the side deck are some upgrades or variant possibilities that u can use as inspiration . The hts and sales ban are for the chummies bcs they hurt a lot. Your own side deck should be oriented around your locals or the changing meta . The nadir package is one engine I suggest to invest in when u find 10 € lying around,sub out the frightfur engine for it and add the 3rd high spirits and pls the sanctifire is straight out the gates of hell DO NOT play it . Side effects are a lot FTK locks and no more friends. But who am I to tell you. Ostinato stands for the melodious engine which is strong but need extradeck and main deck place( and I didn't test this yet).you could play the blue eyes link 1 for a dragon lock with sanctifire or playing a small branded engine in bewd.Dragoon is a possibility with the 1 dark magician or hex in the side.king of the swamp can be an extender if your fusions got negated , I'd recommend playing 2 polys if you play this. Btw no 1 priority should be getting super poly and the targets. then 1 extra granguniol and a minimum of 1 saronir + 1 branded lost and at last nadir package .

I hope this helps

Enjoy :)

deck_excerpt: #Blue-eyes white dragon #Primite #Blue-eyes jet dragon #Neo kaiser sea horse #Dragon's mind
deck_description:
Using blue-eyes jet and neo kaiser for this build. Reason for jet is cuz I just really like the card and hate getting my true light destroyed. As for the neo kaiser, I like having it being sent from field to grave to dump maiden to grave if I know I can summon blue eyes just so I can get my true light out. It can also be an additional special summon if I got blue eyes on field (plus it can make the link 1 spirit).

For the extra deck, I used to play the crimson package with sifr, but when playing it on locals, I just never got to make it, so I scrapped it out and went for more of midrange package. Also was wanted to play ancient fairy life dragon and needed room anyways. It could potentially do an OTK.

For the side, I'm trying out dragon's mind instead of solemn judgement even tho solemn is practically better, but dragon's mind sounds really good on theory so I might take the risk to play it on sides. At the end of the day I'm not that competitive and still wanna have fun.
A work in progress

Prepare for a dazzling dance where the angelic voices of Shopina, Aria, and their melodious kin harmonize with the chaotic charm of Chessy Cat, the bewildering White Rabbit, and the perpetually late March Hare. One moment you're serenading your opponent with graceful fusions like Flowering Etoile, the next you're plunging them into the abyssal embrace of Underworld Goddess or unleashing the devastating might of Accesscode Talker.

But the true artistry lies in the seamless integration of the Maliss cards. Peer into the Maliss in the Mirror and the Maliss in Underground to unlock a hidden dimension of disruption, banishing your opponent's hopes and dreams with Macro Cosmos and the relentless pressure of Dominus Impulse. The cryptic whispers of Maliss Q and the strategic brilliance of Maliss C add layers of intrigue, turning every duel into a high-stakes game of mental chess.

This deck isn't just about pretty melodies; it's a calculated cacophony designed to overwhelm, outmaneuver, and ultimately leave your opponent in stunned silence.
